. Round Robin
How it works

Requests are distributed sequentially:

Request 1 → Server A
Request 2 → Server B
Request 3 → Server C
Request 4 → Server A

Where it fits

Backends are identical

Requests are similar in cost

Stateless services

Pros

Simple

Low overhead

Predictable

Cons (hard truth)

Ignores server load

One slow server degrades overall latency

Used in

NGINX (default)

Kubernetes Service (kube-proxy iptables mode ≈ round-robin)

2. Weighted Round Robin
How it works

Servers get traffic proportional to weight:

A (weight 3), B (weight 1)
→ A, A, A, B

Where it fits

Unequal server capacity

Gradual traffic shift (basic canary)

Pros

Simple capacity awareness

Easy rollout control

Cons

Static weights (no real-time adaptation)

Used in

NGINX

Cloud LBs

Ingress controllers

3. Least Connections
How it works

Request goes to the server with the fewest active connections.

Where it fits

Long-lived connections

Uneven request duration

Pros

Better latency under mixed workloads

Adapts dynamically

Cons

Connection count ≠ CPU usage

Slightly higher overhead

Used in

NGINX

HAProxy

L4/L7 load balancers

4. Weighted Least Connections
How it works

Least connections adjusted by server capacity.

Where it fits

Mixed instance sizes

High concurrency systems

Pros

More accurate than plain least-conn

Cons

Still blind to actual CPU/memory

5. Least Response Time (Latency-based)
How it works

Routes to backend with:

lowest (response_time + active_connections)

Where it fits

Performance-critical APIs

User-facing systems

Pros

Optimizes real user experience

Cons

Requires continuous measurement

Can oscillate under unstable backends

Used in

Advanced proxies

Service meshes

6. Random
How it works

Pick a backend at random.

Why it exists

Surprisingly effective at scale.

Pros

Extremely cheap

Avoids synchronization bias

Cons

Not deterministic

Needs many backends to average out

Used in

High-scale systems

Sometimes combined with “power of two choices”

7. Hash-based (Consistent Hashing)
How it works

A hash of a key determines backend:

hash(user_id) → Server X

Where it fits

Session stickiness

Caching systems

Stateful workloads

Pros

Same client → same backend

Minimal rebalancing on scale changes

Cons

Uneven load if key distribution is skewed

Used in

NGINX (hash)

Service meshes

Distributed caches

8. IP Hash
How it works

Client IP decides backend.

Where it fits

Legacy session stickiness

No cookies allowed

Pros

Simple stickiness

Cons (brutal truth)

Breaks with NAT, proxies, mobile clients

Very uneven in real traffic

9. Power of Two Choices (advanced, underrated)
How it works

Randomly pick two servers

Choose the one with less load

Why it’s powerful

Near-optimal load distribution

Very low overhead

Used in

Large-scale distributed systems

Some modern load balancers internally

10. Queue-based / Adaptive (smart LBs)
How it works

Routes based on:

Queue depth

CPU usage

Latency

Error rate

Where it fits

Mission-critical systems

Highly variable workloads

Pros

Best real-world performance

Cons

Complex

Higher cost

Needs observability

Used in

Service meshes

Custom L7 gateways

Kubernetes-specific reality (important)
Kubernetes Service (default)

iptables mode → probabilistic round-robin

IPVS mode → supports:

Round robin

Least connections

Source hashing

Ingress / L7

Algorithm depends on controller (NGINX, Envoy, etc.)

Supports:

Weighted routing

Canary

Sticky sessions

Service Mesh

Latency-aware

Retry-aware

Circuit-breaker integrated

Algorithm selection (tell-it-like-it-is)
Scenario	Correct Choice
Simple stateless APIs	Round Robin
Unequal server sizes	Weighted RR
Long-lived connections	Least Connections
User-facing latency	Least Response Time
Sessions / cache	Consistent Hash
Massive scale	Random / Power of Two
Mission-critical	Adaptive / Mesh
Cost & speed impact

Simple algorithms = cheaper, faster

Smart algorithms = better UX, higher cost

Wrong algorithm = hidden latency + wasted infra

Final hard truths

Load balancing ≠ just distributing traffic

Algorithms matter more than instance count

Kubernetes alone gives basic balancing

Advanced behavior needs Ingress or Mesh

Senior engineers choose simplicity first, intelligence only when needed

